{"id":"physics/0610271","submitter":"Karol Zyczkowski","authors":"Wojciech Slomczynski and Karol Zyczkowski","title":"Penrose voting system and optimal quota","comments":"12 pages, 2 figures","journal-ref":"Acta Physica Polonica B37, 3133-3143 (2006)","doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"physics.soc-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Systems of indirect voting based on the principle of qualified majority can\nbe analysed using the methods of game theory. In particular, this applies to\nthe voting system in the Council of the European Union, which was recently a\nsubject of a vivid political discussion. The a priori voting power of a voter\nmeasures his potential influence over the decisions of the voting body under a\ngiven decision rule. We investigate a system based on the law of Penrose, in\nwhich each representative in the voting body receives the number of votes (the\nvoting weight) proportional to the square root of the population he or she\nrepresents. Here we demonstrate that for a generic distribution of the\npopulation there exists an optimal quota for which the voting power of any\nstate is proportional to its weight. The optimal quota is shown to decrease\nwith the number of voting countries.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 30 Oct 2006 12:49:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
{"id":"q-bio/0610055","submitter":"Illes Farkas","authors":"Illes J. Farkas, Chuang Wu, Chakra Chennubhotla, Ivet Bahar, Zoltan N.\n  Oltvai","title":"Topological basis of signal integration in the\n  transcriptional-regulatory network of the yeast, Saccharomyces cerevisiae","comments":"Color figures, supplement and free full text article available at\n  http://www.biomedcentral.com/1471-2105/7/478/abstract","journal-ref":"BMC Bioinformatics 2006, 7:478","doi":"10.1186/1471-2105-7-478","report-no":null,"categories":"q-bio.MN q-bio.GN","license":null,"abstract":"  BACKGROUND. Signal recognition and information processing is a fundamental\ncellular function, which in part involves comprehensive transcriptional\nregulatory (TR) mechanisms carried out in response to complex environmental\nsignals in the context of the cell's own internal state. However, the network\ntopological basis of developing such integrated responses remains poorly\nunderstood.\n  RESULTS. By studying the TR network of the yeast Saccharomyces cerevisiae we\nshow that an intermediate layer of transcription factors naturally segregates\ninto distinct subnetworks. In these topological units transcription factors are\ndensely interlinked in a largely hierarchical manner and respond to external\nsignals by utilizing a fraction of these subnets.\n  CONCLUSIONS. As transcriptional regulation represents the \"slow\" component of\noverall information processing, the identified topology suggests a model in\nwhich successive waves of transcriptional regulation originating from distinct\nfractions of the TR network control robust integrated responses to complex\nstimuli.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Mon, 30 Oct 2006 09:19:53 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
